x4freetext: 25 cm in diam. and 20cm thick on rotatable arm
The crystal was also protected from the stray gamma
radiation by a cylindrical lead jacket 5 cm thick.
The uncertainty in the deadtime introduced a
maximum uncertainty of about 3% in the data.
CNPD: corrected 4-dig. year
SD: SF9=EXP deleted from REACTION code in
Subents 002-005. REL-REF moved to Subent 005. BIB
update. Data were re-digitized in Subents 002,005.
The targets were found to contain
about 60 % B-11 by weight, with O, Si and C
constituting the major contaminants.
A superposition of unbacked self-supporting boron
targets. The foils were made by the method of Erskine
and Gemmell (see REL-REF) in which the boron is heated
by electron bombardment and evaporated onto glass
slides.
The entire yield curve was taken in a single run under
the final optimum conditions developed during the
experiment. Several times during the run, one point (at
8 MeV) was checked in order to ensure that the target
and electronics were remaining stable.

x4freetext: A boron target deposited on a "thick" gold disk which
was "wobbled" about the beam in a wobble target. In the
present work, the wobble target system was used only
in taking angular distributions up to 5.6 MeV.
A boron target evaporated onto a thin (0.0075 mm) gold
backing. Angular distributions from Ep = 5.5 to 9.5 MeV
were obtained with targets of this type.
A superposition of un backed self-supporting boron
targets. One set of six single films that was used in
several runs was analysed by observing the spectrum of
3.0 MeV alpha particles elastically scattered from each
foil. The targets were found to contain about 60% B-11
by weight, with O, Si and C constituting the major
contaminants. The yield curves reported here and the
angular distributions above Ep = 9.50 MeV were obtained
with this last target system.
Targets up to about 0.5 mg/cm2 thick were used.
